<br>
However, I would like to make an observation, if I may. Since this treatise is clearly designed to be comprehensive, it must tidy up any assumptions it makes with careful provisos, rather than merely assuming them true for all players, when of course, little in fact is.<br>
<br>
There are two implicit assumptions touched on in this thread, both in passing, and not directly to do with the use of the Mod Rod 2 spell. Both of these might be true for many or even the vast majority of Magi, but they are not universally true, and, specifically, neither are true for myself, as an example. And, sir, I am not unique.<br>
<br>
The first assumption is that a Magician at the very highest levels of the game is always going to be heavily involved in raiding (and hence put raiding efficiency first). From this, many deductions are made, but this assumption is in itself not true for all Magi.<br>
<br>
I will use myself as an example. I am in a tiny guild of friends, by playstyle choice. I have no interest in regular raiding whatsoever, and accept that this means my access to some no drop loot items will be limited if not non-existant. This is the price of independence, which in my case (and for some others to), I more than willingly to pay. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  I spend the vast majority of my playtime either soloing, grouping with friends, questing, or tradeskilling, and only raid with the more friendly guilds on my server on some occasions, for fun, or because a friend needs me. Anyone who might think me or others who make the same choices less skilled in playing the class as a result of simply not wanting to raid more than occasionally would be fooling themselves. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
The second assumption, at least as I read this thread, is that a Magician should always choose Conjuration as their specialization. Whilst I would agree with the author that for a Mage who is a heavy raider, this would be the optimal choice, for someone who has a playstyle such as mine, Evocation looks considerably better, even as an Archmage, but strikingly so before level 60. Indeed, I know from my own mana use and playstyle, that when soloing almost all my mana goes into the FR nukes (mostly Sirocco), when grouping I add in damage shields and sometimes debuffs. Mod rods are used for mana regeneration (now I have a Zlandicar's Heart this is easier, but it was still ok before then), but higher expenditure for Sirocco, Char, Scintillation, etc, would be far too high a price to pay for me just for cheaper mod rods. As for chain summoning pets, I never do this, it is inefficient (and more importantly, I do not enjoy it).<br>
<br>
To give more background, my first character is a High Priestess with close to 200 days played. Archmage Suzanna herself, who I play more these days, has coming up to 100 days of her own. Consequently I know the cleric and magician classes very well. In my case, I selected, for only roleplay reasons initially, a specialization of Evocation for my Magician, and never had any intention whatsoever of playing a support role with her. Suzanna is and will remain,  a damage-dealing nuker. As an evocation specialist, I contend to anyone, that I can still outdamage many conjuration-specialist Magi with Sirocco over time (I have the epic pet, but mostly those Magi I am friendly with also have).<br>
<br>
Suzanna does attend a few raids, and when she does, most of her mana is spent on fire nukes, damage shields and debuffs. She makes an excellent contribution to those raids she attends. If I were to find myself with 'heavy' raiders who want a Magician as mostly or totally a mod-rod vending machine, I would politely avoid raiding with those same people again, no bad feeling, it's just not what I want to do. Given my playstyle/roleplay choices, evocation is the *only* choice that makes sense at this time, as Sirocco beats everything else hands down against many creatures for damage per mana point, in soloing and grouping situations, and the other conjure nukes are awfully poor (and highly resisted) compared to the evocation options.<br>
<br>
In summary, let me state, that if this thread is going to be a truly balanced assessment of the issues it addresses, it should carefully note how choices of different playstyles might lead to different conclusions in some circumstances. Be aware, there are many very experienced and talented players who choose other paths through Norrath, and such choices are not inferior, merely different. Perspective must be held, sir, at all times.<br>
<br>
/bow<br>
<br>
Mighty Mage Suzanna<br>
