As a compromise, I assumed 200% Conjuration Specialization, but no <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Spell Casting Mastery</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> or <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Mana Preservation III</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  I stated my assumption <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>explicity</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> not</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> implicitly, and I think my conclusions are well served by this simplification.  Please note, from the first post in the series, that with 50% <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Specialization: Conjuration</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Spell Casting Mastery 2</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, the mana savings are 10%, exactly the same as my assumption, and nearly the same as having a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Mana Preservation III</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> focus item, such as an <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Obulos Death Shroud</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  So I think my assumptions and conclusions hold under a variety of circumstances.  Even with only 50% specialization and no AA skills, the difference is only 0.03 less mana per hit point.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> As an evocation specialist, I contend to anyone, that I can still outdamage many conjuration-specialist Magi with Sirocco over time.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->This is a topic for another thread, but this may well not be the case, not since <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Shock of Fiery Blades</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  While once my favorite nuke, I have abandoned it since becoming an <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> ArchMage</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
